   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   SQUARE D: Square D Co., Palatine, Ill., named Creswell,
Munsell, Fultz &amp; Zirbel, a Young &amp; Rubicam unit in Cedar
Rapids, Iowa, to administer its estimated $30 million
world-wide account. Young &amp; Rubicam offices in Europe, Latin
America and the Far East will also work on the business.
Square D, a maker of electrical equipment, previously had its
ad assignments spread over nine agencies.
                                                                                                       

   CRUISE FINALISTS: Royal Caribbean Cruise Line, Miami, said
it selected four finalists in the review of its $30
million-to-$35 million ad account: Geer, DuBois; Rosenfeld,
Sirowitz, Humphrey & Strauss; Martin Agency; and the
incumbent, Chiat/Day/Mojo. A decision is expected in early
October.
                                                                                                       

   AMERICAN EXPRESS: Retaliating against Visa's ad campaign
prompting merchants to persuade consumers to use only Visa
cards, American Express yesterday ran a newspaper ad
reminding merchants of the benefits of offering its card.
"When you consider the profits the American Express card
delivers to your business, you'll realize Visa's just
spinning their wheels," the ad said, making fun of a gimmicky
profit "wheel" Visa offered to merchants.
                                                                                                       

   GREEN AD: Marcal Paper Mills next month begins airing a TV
ad pitching its new paper towels made from 100% recycled
paper. The commercial, created by Berenter Greenhouse &amp;
Webster, plays on the strategies other paper-towel makers use
to win consumers, like lint-free claims, color variety or
sweepstakes offers. "If you care about the environment . . .
we've just made your decision a lot easier," the ad says.
"Think of what you can save."
